A function $\|\cdot\|:V\to\mathbb{R}$ is a \emph{norm} if for all $v,w\in V$ and $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$:
(1) $\|v\|\ge 0$ and $\|v\|=0$ iff $v=0$;
(2) $\|\lambda v\|=|\lambda|\,\|v\|$;
(3) $\|v+w\|\le \|v\|+\|w\|$.

An \emph{inner product} on a vector space $V$ is a map $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle:V\times V\to\mathbb{R}$ such that for all $u,v,w\in V$ and $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$:
(1) $\langle v,v\rangle\ge 0$ and $\langle v,v\rangle=0$ iff $v=0$;
(2) $\langle v,w\rangle=\langle w,v\rangle$;
(3) $\langle \alpha v,w\rangle=\alpha\langle v,w\rangle$;
(4) $\langle v,w+u\rangle=\langle v,w\rangle+\langle v,u\rangle$.

For $A\subseteq X$:
- $A$ is \emph{dense} in $X$ if for every $x\in X$ and every $\varepsilon>0$ there exists $a\in A$ such that $\|x-a\|<\varepsilon$;
- $X$ is \emph{separable} if it contains a countable dense subset;
- the closure of $A$ is denoted $\overline A$.

Let $H$ have an orthonormal basis $(\varphi^{(j)})_{j\ge1}$. Then for every $v\in H$:
(1) $v=\sum_{j=1}^\infty \langle v,\varphi^{(j)}\rangle\varphi^{(j)}$;
(2) $\|v\|^2=\sum_{j=1}^\infty |\langle v,\varphi^{(j)}\rangle|^2$ (Parseval);
(3) $H^*\cong H$ via the Riesz representation map.

Let $A\in\mathcal L(H)$ satisfy:
(1) $\ker A=\{0\}$;
(2) $A$ is symmetric;
(3) $A$ is compact.
Then there exists a countable set of eigenpairs $(\varphi^{(j)},\lambda_j)$ such that $(\varphi^{(j)})$ is an ONB of $H$, each $A\varphi^{(j)}=\lambda_j\varphi^{(j)}$, and $\lambda_j\to 0$.
